diff --git a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp
index 934156f04f7f..327ce4454df1 100644
--- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp
@@ -2846,6 +2846,19 @@ static Instruction *foldGEPOfPhi(GetElementPtrInst &GEP, PHINode *PN,
   if (DI != -1 && !PN->hasOneUse())
     return nullptr;

+  // Intersect flags across all incoming GEPs feeding the PHI to avoid
+  // strengthening assumptions when folding. Only preserve a flag if it
+  // holds for all incoming GEPs.
+  bool AllInBounds = cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->isInBounds();
+  bool AllNUW = cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->hasNoUnsignedWrap();
+  bool AllNUSW = cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->hasNoUnsignedSignedWrap();
+  for (unsigned OpIdx = 1, E = PN->getNumOperands(); OpIdx != E; ++OpIdx) {
+    auto *OpG = cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(OpIdx));
+    AllInBounds &= OpG->isInBounds();
+    AllNUW &= OpG->hasNoUnsignedWrap();
+    AllNUSW &= OpG->hasNoUnsignedSignedWrap();
+  }
+
   auto *NewGEP = cast<GetElementPtrInst>(Op1->clone());
   if (DI == -1) {
     // All the GEPs feeding the PHI are identical. Clone one down into our
@@ -2869,6 +2882,17 @@ static Instruction *foldGEPOfPhi(GetElementPtrInst &GEP, PHINode *PN,
     NewGEP->setOperand(DI, NewPN);
   }

+  // Apply intersected flags to the newly created GEP.
+  // Start from the cloned flags and clear any that are not common to all inputs.
+  GEPNoWrapFlags NW = cast<GEPOperator>(NewGEP)->getNoWrapFlags();
+  if (!AllInBounds)
+    NW = NW.withoutInBounds();
+  if (!AllNUW)
+    NW = NW.withoutNoUnsignedWrap();
+  if (!AllNUSW)
+    NW = NW.withoutNoUnsignedSignedWrap();
+  NewGEP->setNoWrapFlags(NW);
+
   NewGEP->insertBefore(*GEP.getParent(), GEP.getParent()->getFirstInsertionPt());
   return NewGEP;
 }

reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue:
The transformation sequence turns a phi-of-geps into a phi-of-offsets feeding a single GEP with inbounds nuw flags. In the source, only one incoming GEP was inbounds, while the other was not. By cloning one incoming GEP (the inbounds one) and hoisting it out of the phi, InstCombine incorrectly preserved the inbounds (and nuw) flags on a GEP whose index is a phi that includes a non-inbounds path. This strengthens poison conditions: inbounds GEP from null is poison, whereas the original had a non-inbounds path that produced a defined result. Alive2 reports "Target is more poisonous than source" with %p = null and %c = false.

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
The log shows:
- %gep1 is canonicalized to getelementptr inbounds nuw i8, ptr %p, i64 4.
- %gep2 is canonicalized to getelementptr i8, ptr %p, i64 8 (no inbounds).
- The foldGEPOfPhi rewrites the phi of pointers into %1 = phi i64 [4, %if], [8, %else] and then %2 = getelementptr inbounds nuw i8, ptr %p, i64 %1, preserving both inbounds and nuw from %gep1. This is the first transformation that changes semantics.
- Alive2 demonstrates that the target produces poison while source is not.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
The culprit is foldGEPOfPhi (called from visitGetElementPtrInst). It clones one of the incoming GEPs (Op1) down into the use-site and, when the GEPs differ at one index, replaces the differing operand with a new PHI. However, it blindly preserves the flags (inbounds and no-wrap) from Op1 on the new GEP, even though the other incoming GEP(s) may not have those flags. Inbounds and NUW/NSW are path-sensitive; applying them to a merged operation with a PHI index is only valid if all incoming GEPs have those flags. Failing to intersect/strip flags strengthens assumptions and introduces poison.

4. Proposed Edit Point(s):
Modify foldGEPOfPhi to intersect flags across all incoming GEPs and drop any flag that is not present on all inputs. Specifically:
- Compute AllInBounds, AllNUW, AllNSW by AND'ing the corresponding flags of each incoming GEPOperator feeding the PHI.
- After cloning Op1 to NewGEP (and possibly substituting the differing index with a PHI), clear flags on NewGEP that are not universally true across all inputs.

Edit at llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp lines 2849-2873:

Replace the tail of foldGEPOfPhi to:

  // Track flags across incoming GEPs feeding the PHI.
  bool AllInBounds = cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->isInBounds();
  bool AllNUW = cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->hasNoUnsignedWrap();
  bool AllNSW = cast<GEPOperator>(PN->getOperand(0))->hasNoSignedWrap();

  for (auto I = PN->op_begin() + 1, E = PN->op_end(); I != E; ++I) {
    auto *OpG = dyn_cast<GEPOperator>(*I);
    if (!OpG)
      return nullptr; // Should not happen given previous checks.
    AllInBounds &= OpG->isInBounds();
    AllNUW &= OpG->hasNoUnsignedWrap();
    AllNSW &= OpG->hasNoSignedWrap();
  }

  auto *NewGEP = cast<GetElementPtrInst>(Op1->clone());
  if (DI == -1) {
    // All the GEPs feeding the PHI are identical. Clone one down into our
    // BB so that it can be merged with the current GEP.
  } else {
    // All the GEPs feeding the PHI differ at a single offset. Clone a GEP
    // into the current block so it can be merged, and create a new PHI to
    // set that index.
    PHINode *NewPN;
    {
      IRBuilderBase::InsertPointGuard Guard(Builder);
      Builder.SetInsertPoint(PN);
      NewPN = Builder.CreatePHI(Op1->getOperand(DI)->getType(),
                                PN->getNumOperands());
    }

    for (auto &I : PN->operands())
      NewPN->addIncoming(cast<GEPOperator>(I)->getOperand(DI),
                         PN->getIncomingBlock(I));

    NewGEP->setOperand(DI, NewPN);
  }

  // Intersect flags: only preserve flags that hold for all incoming GEPs.
  if (!AllInBounds)
    NewGEP->setIsInBounds(false);
  if (!AllNUW)
    NewGEP->setHasNoUnsignedWrap(false);
  if (!AllNSW)
    NewGEP->setHasNoSignedWrap(false);

  NewGEP->insertBefore(*GEP.getParent(), GEP.getParent()->getFirstInsertionPt());
  return NewGEP;

Notes:
- GEPOperator exposes isInBounds(), hasNoUnsignedWrap(), hasNoSignedWrap(); GetElementPtrInst exposes setters setIsInBounds(bool), setHasNoUnsignedWrap(bool), setHasNoSignedWrap(bool).
- This keeps flags only when they are valid along all incoming paths, preventing unintended poison.

5. Conclusion:
By intersecting (rather than blindly copying) inbounds and no-wrap flags when folding a GEP over a PHI of GEPs, we avoid strengthening assumptions in the presence of mixed-flag inputs. This fix ensures the transformed IR preserves semantics: the resulting GEP will not be inbounds/NUW unless all incoming GEPs are, and Alive2's reported miscompilation disappears. This change affects only foldGEPOfPhi and is consistent with LLVM’s requirement to conservatively preserve flags through IR transformations.

